A fragile flat world
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman says. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his bestseller to make people aware of the stunning impact of technology on the world economy.
The distance is shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide easy protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in both Europe and the United States have to face the challenges of global competition.
Western consumers who call local companies may be speaking with employees who are thousands of miles away in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limitations of the Friedman analogy.
As someone has said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven."
The world economic activities' contour map shows the peaks of prosperity and the valleys of scarcity.
It not only has this effect, but distance is far from losing its effect.
Even in countries with lower tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, domestic trade far exceeds cross-border trade.
The geographical distance between Seattle and Vancouver is close, but Vancouver's trade with Toronto, which is far away, is much higher than that with nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticism, Friedman still presented an important point of view.
Globalization can be defined as interdependence between different continents, with a history as long as that of humanity, witnessing the migration of races and religions, and witnessing the ancient Silk Road trade between medieval Europe and Asia along the way.
But today's globalization is different, it develops at a faster speed and to a much deeper extent.
Following the completion of the first transatlantic telegraph cable in 1868, Europeans and Americans could communicate with each other in as little as a minute.
In 1919, John Maynard Keynes portrayed a vision of British people in London ordering goods by telephone from around the world and waiting for delivery in the afternoon at home.
But Keynes's Englishmen belonged to the rare case of being extremely wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy goods from all over the world at local supermarkets.
Similar to this, 20 years ago, instant global communication also existed, but was beyond the affordability of most people economically.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an Internet cafe and gain the ability that was previously only accessible to the government, multinational corporations, and a select few individuals or organizations with large budgets.
The sharp decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, nearly two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
However, today, the proportion of American internet users accounts for less than a quarter of the world's users.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has set a new record in human history.
Non-state institutions now have the ability that was previously held by the government.
The status of the nation-state as a global political entity will not change for the time being, but it must learn to share this vast stage with more players, including the Oxford Famine Relief Committee, celebrities like Bono, and global terrorist networks like al-Qaeda.
However, this flattening process is reversible.
It has also happened before.
Between 1914 and 1944, the world economy was highly integrated, but over the next 30 years, interdependence between nations in the global economy steadily decreased.
Not until 1970 did the world economy recover to the level of integration it had once enjoyed, and even then it was still heavily segmented by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was a catalyst for the reversal, and during both World Wars and the Cold War, people witnessed a decrease in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflects more profound issues such as domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics has been unable to adapt to the development of the economy, resulting in an abnormal ideology—fascism and communism reigning supreme at the same time—this pathological development of ideas has caused the division of the nation and the world.
After World War II, Western welfare states spun a safety net to protect those who suffered damage in economic changes, in order to encourage them to accept the returns of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is very similar to Germany in the 20th century.
They are the emerging force troubled by domestic inequality, ceaselessly developing towards nationalism and challenging the dominant power, ultimately triggering a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the US and China's economies are highly interdependent today, Britain and Germany's economies were no less so before 1914.
But such reasoning is not perfect.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
Even if China continues to maintain its high growth rate, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with the US in at least 20 years.
The greater threat to a flat world may be the non-state, cross-state powers unleashed by the spread of technology.
In 2001, on September 11, a non-state network killed more Americans in a surprise attack than the Japanese government did in its attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such a power obtains nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world will undergo a complete upheaval.
At that time, personnel and goods crossing the border will become more difficult.
If the aforementioned forces were to destroy the oil output of the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn like that of the 1930s could be further amplified, strengthening the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two main driving forces of globalization.
To date, policies have further consolidated the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken a leadership role in driving policies to eliminate barriers.
But the previous description of the event may reverse this policy.
Some globalization critics may be willing to see this outcome.
However, such a result, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst-case scenarios in two fields: the reversal of the economic trend toward globalized technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalisation would be further entrenched, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If it's true, a flat world would become a desert.
